Herbert Simon, Oskar Morgenstern, Herman Kahn, Anatol Rapoport, Thomas Schelling, and many others—and places, including the RAND Corporation, the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences, the Cowles Commission for Research and Economics, and the Council on Foreign Relations, that played a key role in putting forth a “Cold War rationality.” Decision makers harnessed this picture of rationality—optimizing, formal, algorithmic, and mechanical—in their quest to understand phenomena as diverse as economic transactions, biological evolution, political elections, international relations, and military strategy. The authors chronicle and illuminate what it meant to be rational in the age of nuclear brinkmanship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  atechnology, economic history, engineering, historical research, united states, cold war, russia, soviet union, 20th century, rationality, sharp minds, powerful politicians, wealthy foundations, top military brass, psychology, sociology, political science, economics, intellectual campaign, rand corporation, center for advanced study, behavioral sciences, council on foreign relations, biological evolution, democracy, international topics, nuclear brinkmanship.1 aDaston, Lorraine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGordin, Michael D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKlein, Judy L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSturm, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022604663140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226046778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226046778/original  